04192nam a22005655i 9780300148572DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20181999ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001485727 a10.12987/97803001485722doi  a(DE-B1597)486549  a(OCoLC)1024039980  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aML240b.S89 1999eb 7aMUS0240002bisacsh04a780/.9422200aNew World Symphonies /ced. by Arielle Saiber, Stefano Ugo Baldassarri. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2018] 4c©1999  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER ONE. The Legacy of the Sorrow Songs -- tCHAPTER TWO. Hiawatha Fever: The Legacy of Longfellow -- tCHAPTER THREE. New Worlds of Terror: The Legacy of Poe -- tCHAPTER FOUR. New World Songs: The Legacy of Whitman -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Beyond the Frontier: New World Landscape -- tCHAPTER Six. Broadway, Hollywood, and the Accidental Beauties of Silly Songs -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. New World Rhythm: The Spread of Jazz -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis groundbreaking book shows for the first time the profound and transformative influence of American literature, music, and mythology on European music. Although the impact of the European tradition on American composers is widely acknowledged, Jack Sullivan demonstrates that an even more powerful musical current has flowed from the New World to the Old. The spread of rock and roll around the world, the author contends, is only the latest chapter in a cross-cultural story that began in the nineteenth century with Gottschalk in Paris and Dvorák in New York.Sullivan brings popular and canonical culture into his wide-ranging discussion. He explores the effects on European music of American authors as diverse as Twain, DuBois, Melville, and Langston Hughes, examining in particular Dvorák’s fascination with Longfellow, the obsession of Debussy and Ravel with Poe, and the inspiration Whitman provided for Holst, Vaughan Williams, and dozens more. Sullivan uncovers the African American musical influence on Europe, beginning with spirituals and culminating in the impact of jazz on Stravinsky, Bartók, Walton, and others. He analyzes the lure of Hollywood and Broadway for such composers as Weill, Korngold, and Britten and considers the power of the American landscape-from the remoteness of the prairie to the brutal energy of the American city. In European music, Sullivan finds, American culture and mythology continue to resonate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMusiczEuropexAmerican influences. 0aMusiczUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / International.2bisacsh1 aBaldassarri, Stefano Ugo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSaiber, Arielle, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z97831105380140 cprintz978030007231040uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030014857240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300148572423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300148572/original  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY